## 📦 Box Plot — What It Is & How to Read It

A **box plot** (box-and-whisker plot) visually summarizes the **distribution** of a dataset using 5 key statistics.

### Visual Structure
```
Min   Q1   Median  Q3   Max
 |----[====|========]-----|
      ↑                  ↑
   Lower Whisker    Upper Whisker
```

### Reading a Box Plot

| Part | What It Means |
|---|---|
| **Box (left edge)** | 25th percentile (Q1) — 25% of data falls below this |
| **Line inside box** | Median (50th percentile) — middle value |
| **Box (right edge)** | 75th percentile (Q3) — 75% of data falls below this |
| **Box width** | IQR (Interquartile Range) = Q3 - Q1, shows the middle 50% spread |
| **Whiskers** | Extend to min/max values (excluding outliers) |
| **Dots beyond whiskers** | Outliers — unusually high or low values |

### What It Tells Us in the Crop Dataset

| Feature | Insight |
|---|---|
| **Wide box** | High variability — strong signal for ML model |
| **Tight box** | Low variability — less discriminative feature |
| **Outliers** | Crops with unusual requirements (e.g. very high rainfall) |

